(* Canonicalization *)

1 - Purpose
    -------

    This document records the canonical syntactic conventions adopted across
    all Rocq developments under Proofcase/theories/T###/.  We derived these
    conventions by surveying T001, T002, and T003, identifying the patterns
    that appear most consistently, and resolving the points of divergence
    into a single standard.


2 - File Naming
    -----------

    2.1  Prefixes

         We prefix construction and reduction files with R##__ and
         proof-theory files with P##__.

    2.2  Numbering

         We begin numbering at 00 and increment sequentially.  When a file
         is removed we note the gap in the README rather than reusing the
         number.

    2.3  Suffix

         We write the descriptive portion of the filename in PascalCase,
         with underscores separating logical words.

             R00__Degree_Framework.v
             R04__Verification_Hilbert_Syntax.v
             P03__Undecidability.v

         We give export and extraction files a numeric prefix like all
         others, and never use a letter prefix such as RX.


3 - Header Comment
    --------------

    We place a comment on line 1 of every .v file containing the exact
    filename:

        (* R04__Verification_Hilbert_Syntax.v *)

    We require the string inside the comment to match the filename on disk
    character-for-character, including the .v extension.

        GOOD:  (* R05__Effectivity.v *)
        BAD:   (* R05__Effectivity *)
        BAD:   (* RX__Carryless_Pairing_Export.v *)  when file is R04__...


4 - Imports
    -------

    4.1  Standard library

         We write the standard-library imports on a single line, listing
         modules in alphabetical order.

             From Coq Require Import Arith Bool List PeanoNat.

    4.2  Notation imports

         We place notation imports on a separate line immediately after the
         Require Import.

             Import ListNotations.

    4.3  Scope directives

         We place scope directives on separate lines after notation imports.

             Open Scope Z_scope.
             Open Scope string_scope.

    4.4  Project imports

         We use From T### Require Import for project-internal modules.
         When we import more than two modules, we use multi-line formatting
         with two-space indentation:

             From T002 Require Import
               R01__Foundation_Fibonacci
               R04__Verification_Hilbert_Syntax
               R05__Verification_Hilbert_Checker.


5 - Naming Conventions
    ------------------

    5.1  Types and inductives

         We name types and inductives in PascalCase.

             Form   Expr   Params   OForm

    5.2  Constructors

         We name constructors in PascalCase, optionally prefixed by the
         type initial.

             F_Bot   F_Imp   Ax_K   Ax_S   Ax_EFQ

    5.3  Definitions and functions

         We name definitions and computational functions in snake_case.

             fib_pair   even_band   code_output   toggle_code

    5.4  Propositions and predicates (Prop-valued)

         We name Prop-valued definitions in PascalCase.

             Thm   CubicSat   ClosedCode   CorrectCode   RepresentationBound

    5.5  Boolean tests

         We give boolean decision functions an is_ prefix and write the
         remainder in snake_case.

             is_even   is_odd   is_axiom   is_K

    5.6  Lemma and theorem names

         We follow a subject_property pattern in snake_case.

             div2_two          (subject: div2, property: two)
             form_eqb_refl     (subject: form_eqb, property: refl)
             EvalRM_deterministic

         When the subject is a PascalCase name we preserve its casing in
         the lemma name.

    5.7  Record fields

         We name record fields with a consistent short prefix per record,
         followed by the field name.

             uc_poly   uc_U   uc_ix_u
             as_pf     as_target

    5.8  Single-letter names

         We permit single-letter names only for Section variables.

             Variable P : Params.

         We do not use single-letter names for top-level Definitions.

             BAD:   Definition F (n : nat) := ...
             GOOD:  Definition fib (n : nat) := ...


6 - Scoping Constructs
    -------------------

    6.1  Bare top-level

         We place pure definitions that take no shared parameters at the
         bare top level.

             Definition degree (e : Expr) : nat := ...

    6.2  Section

         We use Sections for parameterized proof blocks whose definitions
         and lemmas share Variables or Hypotheses.

             Section Carryless_Correctness.
               Variable P : Params.
               Hypothesis Z_sound : forall n, sumF (Z P n) = n.
               ...
             End Carryless_Correctness.

    6.3  Module

         We reserve Modules for concrete instantiations and realizations.

             Module Realization.
               Definition P0 : Params := ...
             End Realization.

         We do not mix the two: if a file uses a Section for parameterized
         proofs, we do not also wrap definitions in a Module unless those
         definitions form a concrete instance.


7 - Comment Style
    -------------

    7.1  Block banner

         We use block banners only for major section separators and set
         them at 73 characters wide:

             (*****************************************************************)
             (*                                                               *)
             (*  Section Title                                                *)
             (*                                                               *)
             (*****************************************************************)

    7.2  Doc comments

         We place a doc comment directly above every top-level Definition,
         Fixpoint, Lemma, and Theorem.  We write the comment in multi-line
         form with the text indented inside the delimiters, and we leave a
         blank line between the closing *) and the definition:

             (*
               Sum of Fibonacci values over a list of indices.
             *)

             Fixpoint sumF (xs : list nat) : nat := ...

         We omit comments only for trivial re-exports in API files.

    7.3  No trailing inline comments

         We place explanatory comments on their own line above the
         definition, not inline after the code.

             BAD: Definition two_j_minus1 (j : nat) := Nat.pred (two j). (* 2j-1 *)
             
             BAD:
             (* 2j - 1, with Nat.pred 0 = 0. *)
             Definition two_j_minus1 (j : nat) := Nat.pred (two j).
             
             ALMOST:

             (*
             2j - 1, with Nat.pred 0 = 0. 
             *)
             Definition two_j_minus1 (j : nat) := Nat.pred (two j).

             GOOD:

             (*
               2j - 1, with Nat.pred 0 = 0. 
             *)
             
             Definition two_j_minus1 (j : nat) := Nat.pred (two j).




8 - Proof Style
    -----------

    8.1  One-liner proofs

         When a proof requires at most three tactic steps we write it on a
         single line:

             Proof. reflexivity. Qed.
             Proof. vm_compute. reflexivity. Qed.
             Proof. intro n. simpl. lia. Qed.

    8.2  Multi-line proofs

         We place Proof. on its own line and indent tactics by two spaces.

             Proof.
               intros x y.
               unfold unpair.
               rewrite Hx.
               reflexivity.
             Qed.

    8.3  Sub-goal markers

         We use bullets for sub-goals, never braces.

             First level:   -
             Second level:  +
             Third level:   *
             Fourth level:  --

             GOOD:
             - apply IH. lia.
             - rewrite Hx.
               + exact H1.
               + exact H2.

             BAD:
             { apply IH. lia. }

    8.4  Computational witnesses

         We write vm_compute examples in one-liner form:

             Proof. vm_compute. reflexivity. Qed.


9 - API and Export Patterns
    -----------------------

    9.1  API boundary files

         We re-export public definitions by aliasing them:

             Definition Thm : nat -> Prop :=
               R16__Sigma_Reduction.Thm.

         We seal internals at the end of the file:

             Global Opaque internal_lemma_1.
             Global Opaque internal_lemma_2.

    9.2  Numbered theorem aliases

         We assign stable paper-facing labels with a short prefix, and
         we place these only in API boundary files, not in working files.

             Theorem SR01_sigma_reduction : ...
             Theorem SR02_thm_reduces_to_cubic : ...

    9.3  Extraction files

         We give extraction files a numeric prefix and set the extraction
         output directory to match the actual artifacts directory:

             Extraction Language OCaml.
             Set Extraction Output Directory "artifacts".

             Extraction "output_name.ml" fn1 fn2 fn3.

         We end with Print Assumptions for the principal theorems:

             Print Assumptions unpair_pair.
             Print Assumptions pair_inj.

    9.4  Print Assumptions

         We close every endpoint file (extraction, final theorem, bounded
         universality) with Print Assumptions for each principal result.


10 - README Structure
     ----------------

     10.1  Format

           We write READMEs as plain text with a (* README *) header and
           numbered sections.

               (* README *)

               1 - Description
                   -----------
                   ...

               2 - Repository Tree
                   ---------------
                   .
                   +-- README
                   |      (This file.)
                   +-- R00__First_File.v
                   ...

     10.2  Tree accuracy

           We require every filename in the repository tree to match the
           filename on disk character-for-character.  When we rename a
           file, we update the README in the same change.

     10.3  Additional sections

           We add further sections as needed (Regeneration, Semantics, etc.)
           and number them sequentially from 3 onward.


11 - Known Deviations
     ----------------

     The following deviations from this guide exist in the current codebase.
     We track them here for correction.

     T001
     ----

     (i)    File numbering starts at R01, not R00.

     (ii)   The README lists RX__Carryless_Pairing_Export.v but the file on
            disk is R04__Carryless_Pairing_Export.v.

     (iii)  The header comment in R04 reads (* RX__Carryless_Pairing_Export.v *)
            instead of (* R04__Carryless_Pairing_Export.v *).

     (iv)   R02 uses { } braces for sub-goals instead of bullets.

     (v)    R01 has no Section despite all definitions sharing P : Params.

     (vi)   The extraction output directory is set to "witness" instead of
            "artifacts".

     (vii)  Single-letter top-level definitions: F, B.

     (viii) Mixed casing: sumF (camelCase) alongside fib_pair (snake_case).

     T002
     ----

     (i)    R01__Foundation_Fibonacci.v inherits the T001 naming: F, sumF, B.

     (ii)   R00__Degree_Framework.v has no doc comments above definitions.

     (iii)  The header comment in R01 reads (* R01__Fibonacci.v *) instead of
            (* R01__Foundation_Fibonacci.v *).

     T003
     ----

     (i)    The header comment in R05 reads (* R05__Effectivity *), missing
            the .v extension.

     (ii)   R01__Coeff_types.v has no header comment.

     (iii)  R00__VarMap.v has no doc comments (auto-generated, but we expect
            them regardless).

     (iv)   The numbering gap at R06 is not noted in the README.
